<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="358" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1275,1950]" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1419,1445]" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">Remarks</emphasis>
. The only known female of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Saguiah &amp; Molin &amp; Tavares" authorityYear="2020" box="[630,700,1419,1445]" class="Insecta" family="Chalcididae" genus="Chalcis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="boi">
<emphasis box="[630,700,1419,1445]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">C. boi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished from females of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Saguiah &amp; Molin &amp; Tavares" authorityYear="2020" box="[1079,1256,1419,1445]" class="Insecta" family="Chalcididae" genus="Chalcis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="intervalensis">
<emphasis box="[1079,1256,1419,1445]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">C. intervalensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Saguiah &amp; Molin &amp; Tavares" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Cameron" baseAuthorityYear="1909" box="[1271,1429,1419,1446]" class="Insecta" family="Chalcididae" genus="Chalcis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ornatifrons">
<emphasis box="[1271,1290,1419,1445]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1304,1429,1419,1445]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">ornatifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Cameron" baseAuthorityYear="1909" box="[200,339,1455,1482]" class="Insecta" family="Chalcididae" genus="Chalcis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pilicauda">
<emphasis box="[200,219,1455,1481]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[233,339,1455,1481]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">pilicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its more robust body (
<figureCitation box="[633,713,1455,1481]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1919,1943]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,453,1896]" captionTargetId="figure-140@4.[151,1435,453,1896]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1a–f. Chalcis boi sp. nov., holotype female: a, habitus, lateral, b, habitus, dorsal; c, head, frontal; d, head, lateral; e, protarsal claw; f, metafemur and metatibia, outer face." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4296701" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4296701/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">Fig. 1a</figureCitation>
), the 
<taxonomicName box="[779,897,1456,1482]" class="Crustacea (awaiting allocation)" family="Crustacea (awaiting allocation)" genus="Mesosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Crustacea (awaiting allocation)" pageId="5" pageNumber="379" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">mesosoma</taxonomicName>
being entirely black (
<figureCitation box="[1145,1260,1455,1482]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1919,1943]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,453,1896]" captionTargetId="figure-140@4.[151,1435,453,1896]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1a–f. Chalcis boi sp. nov., holotype female: a, habitus, lateral, b, habitus, dorsal; c, head, frontal; d, head, lateral; e, protarsal claw; f, metafemur and metatibia, outer face." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4296701" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4296701/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">Figs 1a, b</figureCitation>
), and the malar space being almost as long as height of an eye (
<figureCitation box="[695,777,1491,1517]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1919,1943]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,453,1896]" captionTargetId="figure-140@4.[151,1435,453,1896]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1a–f. Chalcis boi sp. nov., holotype female: a, habitus, lateral, b, habitus, dorsal; c, head, frontal; d, head, lateral; e, protarsal claw; f, metafemur and metatibia, outer face." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4296701" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4296701/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">Fig. 1c</figureCitation>
). It is further distinguished by the ovipositor sheath being obliquely truncate apically (
<figureCitation box="[464,576,1527,1554]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1169,1193]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1145]" captionTargetId="figure-20@5.[151,1435,181,1145]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2a–d. Chalcis boi sp. nov., holotype female: a, metatarsus, lateral; b, propodeum; c, gaster, lateral; d, ovipositor sheath, lateral." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4296703" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4296703/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">Figs 2c, d</figureCitation>
), and metatarsomere 5 being slightly longer than any of tarsomeres 1–4 (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1169,1193]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1145]" captionTargetId="figure-20@5.[151,1435,181,1145]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2a–d. Chalcis boi sp. nov., holotype female: a, metatarsus, lateral; b, propodeum; c, gaster, lateral; d, ovipositor sheath, lateral." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4296703" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4296703/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">Fig. 2a</figureCitation>
). Among the New World species, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Saguiah &amp; Molin &amp; Tavares" authorityYear="2020" box="[559,627,1563,1589]" class="Insecta" family="Chalcididae" genus="Chalcis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="boi">
<emphasis box="[559,627,1563,1589]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">C. boi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Burks, 1940" authorityName="Burks" authorityYear="1940" box="[771,1070,1563,1589]" class="Insecta" family="Chalcididae" genus="Chalcis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="megalomis">
<emphasis box="[771,924,1563,1589]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">C. megalomis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Burks, B. D." box="[931,1070,1563,1589]" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" pagination="237 - 354" refId="ref18392" refString="Burks, B. D. (1940) Revision of the chalcid-flies of the tribe Chalcidini in America north of Mexico. Proceedings of the United States National Museum, 88, 237 - 354. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00963801.88 - 3082.237" type="journal article" year="1940">Burks, 1940</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, recorded from the 
<collectingCountry box="[1287,1436,1563,1589]" name="United States of America" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">United States</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[201,290,1599,1625]" name="Mexico" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">Mexico</collectingCountry>
. Females of both have the 
<taxonomicName box="[605,723,1600,1626]" class="Crustacea (awaiting allocation)" family="Crustacea (awaiting allocation)" genus="Mesosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Crustacea (awaiting allocation)" pageId="5" pageNumber="379" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">mesosoma</taxonomicName>
entirely black, the protarsal claws ventrally with basal spines followed by few curved setae, the metafemur ventrally with similar-sized teeth along the outer margin, the petiole without longitudinal carinae, and the ovipositor sheath obliquely truncate apically. However, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Saguiah &amp; Molin &amp; Tavares" authorityYear="2020" box="[1194,1263,1671,1697]" class="Insecta" family="Chalcididae" genus="Chalcis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="boi">
<emphasis box="[1194,1263,1671,1697]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">C. boi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Burks" authorityYear="1940" class="Insecta" family="Chalcididae" genus="Chalcis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="megalomis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">C. megalomis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the gaster having yellow stripes (uniformly brown in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Burks" authorityYear="1940" box="[901,1053,1707,1733]" class="Insecta" family="Chalcididae" genus="Chalcis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="megalomis">
<emphasis box="[901,1053,1707,1733]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">C. megalomis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), the lower face bulging above the clypeus (
<figureCitation box="[251,330,1743,1770]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1919,1943]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,453,1896]" captionTargetId="figure-140@4.[151,1435,453,1896]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1a–f. Chalcis boi sp. nov., holotype female: a, habitus, lateral, b, habitus, dorsal; c, head, frontal; d, head, lateral; e, protarsal claw; f, metafemur and metatibia, outer face." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4296701" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4296701/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">Fig. 1d</figureCitation>
) (not bulging in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Burks" authorityYear="1940" box="[518,671,1743,1769]" class="Insecta" family="Chalcididae" genus="Chalcis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="megalomis">
<emphasis box="[518,671,1743,1769]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">C. megalomis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), the malar space 0.8× eye height (0.7× eye height in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Burks" authorityYear="1940" box="[1267,1420,1743,1769]" class="Insecta" family="Chalcididae" genus="Chalcis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="megalomis">
<emphasis box="[1267,1420,1743,1769]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">C. megalomis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), the mesoscutellum distinctly convex (almost flat in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Burks" authorityYear="1940" box="[723,875,1779,1805]" class="Insecta" family="Chalcididae" genus="Chalcis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="megalomis">
<emphasis box="[723,875,1779,1805]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">C. megalomis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), the metafemur stronger and longer (not as strong or long in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Burks" authorityYear="1940" box="[267,421,1815,1841]" class="Insecta" family="Chalcididae" genus="Chalcis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="megalomis">
<emphasis box="[267,421,1815,1841]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">C. megalomis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, see 
<bibRefCitation author="Burks, B. D." box="[478,611,1815,1841]" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" pagination="237 - 354" refId="ref18392" refString="Burks, B. D. (1940) Revision of the chalcid-flies of the tribe Chalcidini in America north of Mexico. Proceedings of the United States National Museum, 88, 237 - 354. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00963801.88 - 3082.237" type="journal article" year="1940">Burks 1940</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 11j), the metatibia with a robust apical spine (
<figureCitation box="[1179,1254,1815,1842]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1919,1943]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,453,1896]" captionTargetId="figure-140@4.[151,1435,453,1896]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1a–f. Chalcis boi sp. nov., holotype female: a, habitus, lateral, b, habitus, dorsal; c, head, frontal; d, head, lateral; e, protarsal claw; f, metafemur and metatibia, outer face." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4296701" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4296701/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">Fig. 1f</figureCitation>
) (triangular and acute in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Burks" authorityYear="1940" box="[246,400,1851,1877]" class="Insecta" family="Chalcididae" genus="Chalcis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="megalomis">
<emphasis box="[246,400,1851,1877]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">C. megalomis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and the petiole 2.4× as long as wide (1.5× as long as wide in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Burks" authorityYear="1940" box="[1107,1260,1851,1877]" class="Insecta" family="Chalcididae" genus="Chalcis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="358" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="megalomis">
<emphasis box="[1107,1260,1851,1877]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="358">C. megalomis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
